# Building API Pages for External Integrations

Business Central's API pages expose your data as OData v4 endpoints, enabling seamless integration with Power BI, Power Automate, and external systems.

## Basic API Page Structure

```al
page 50200 "Customer API"
{
  PageType = API;
  APIPublisher = 'yourcompany';
  APIGroup = 'core';
  APIVersion = 'v1.0';
  EntityName = 'customer';
  EntitySetName = 'customers';
  SourceTable = Customer;
  DelayedInsert = true;
  ODataKeyFields = SystemId;

  layout
  {
    area(Content)
    {
      group(General)
      {
        field(id; Rec.SystemId)
        {
          Caption = 'Id';
          Editable = false;
        }
        field(number; Rec."No.")
        {
          Caption = 'Number';
        }
        field(displayName; Rec.Name)
        {
          Caption = 'Display Name';
        }
        field(email; Rec."E-Mail")
        {
          Caption = 'Email';
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

## Accessing the Endpoint

```http
GET https://api.businesscentral.dynamics.com/v2.0/{tenantId}/{environment}/api/yourcompany/core/v1.0/companies({companyId})/customers
```

## Adding Filtering Support

OData filtering works automatically:
```http
GET /customers?$filter=country eq 'GB'&$top=50&$orderby=displayName
```

## Securing Your API

- Use **OAuth 2.0** with Azure AD app registration
- Apply **permission sets** to control access
- Consider **rate limiting** for external consumers

## Best Practices

1. Always use `SystemId` (GUID) as the OData key ÃÂ¢ÃÂÃÂ never use business keys like document numbers
2. Use `DelayedInsert = true` for API pages to handle complex insertions
3. Implement proper error handling with meaningful error messages
4. Version your APIs (`v1.0`, `v2.0`) to avoid breaking changes

# Optimizing AL Code for Performance

Poor performance is one of the most common issues in Business Central extensions. This guide covers the most impactful optimizations.

## Filter Early, Filter Often

The golden rule: **filter data before you loop through it**.

```al
// BAD - Fetches all customers, checks in AL
Customer.FindSet();
repeat
  if Customer."Country/Region Code" = 'GB' then
    ProcessCustomer(Customer);
until Customer.Next() = 0;

// GOOD - SQL does the filtering
Customer.SetRange("Country/Region Code", 'GB');
if Customer.FindSet() then
  repeat
    ProcessCustomer(Customer);
  until Customer.Next() = 0;
```

## Use Temporary Tables

```al
var
  TempSalesLine: Record "Sales Line" temporary;
begin
  // Load filtered data once
  SalesLine.SetRange("Document No.", SalesHeader."No.");
  if SalesLine.FindSet() then
    repeat
      TempSalesLine := SalesLine;
      TempSalesLine.Insert();
    until SalesLine.Next() = 0;

  // Process from temp table (fast, in-memory)
  if TempSalesLine.FindSet() then
    repeat
      // Process...
    until TempSalesLine.Next() = 0;
end;
```

## Avoid CalcFields in Loops

```al
// BAD - Database hit on every iteration
repeat
  Customer.CalcFields("Balance (LCY)"); // Expensive!
  if Customer."Balance (LCY)" > 10000 then
    SendAlert(Customer);
until Customer.Next() = 0;

// GOOD - Use FlowFields with SetAutoCalcFields
Customer.SetAutoCalcFields("Balance (LCY)");
Customer.FindSet();
repeat
  if Customer."Balance (LCY)" > 10000 then
    SendAlert(Customer);
until Customer.Next() = 0;
```

## Key Performance Tips

| Pattern | Performance | Note |
|---------|-------------|------|
| `FindSet()` + loop | Fast | Best for reading multiple records |
| `Get()` | Very fast | Single record by primary key |
| `FindFirst()` | Moderate | Adds `TOP 1` to SQL |
| `Count()` | Slow | Full table scan without filter |
| `CalcFields` in loop | Very slow | Avoid! |

## Profiling Your Code

Use the **AL Profiler** in VS Code to identify bottlenecks:
1. Open Command Palette ÃÂ¢ÃÂÃÂ `AL: Start CPU Profile`
2. Perform the slow operation
3. Stop the profile and analyze the flamegraph

